160":"1160","1180":"1180","1214":"1214","1223":"1223","1200":"1200","1167":"1167","antes 1200":"vóór 1200","1208":"1208","Viseu, Portugal":"Viseu, Portugal","Lisboa, Lisboa, Portugal":"Lisboa, Lisboa, Portugal","Portugal":"Portugal"},"en":{"1153–1223":"1153–1223","1167–Female":"1167–Deceased","1180–Female":"1180–Deceased","1186–Female":"1186–Deceased","1187–Female":"1187–Deceased","1190–Male":"1190–Deceased","1150–1200":"1150–1200","1141–Male":"1141–Deceased","1143–Male":"1143–Deceased","1200–Male":"1200–Deceased","1160–1208":"1160–1208","1167–1214":"1167–1214","1190":"1190","1143":"1143","1187":"1187","1153":"1153","1186":"1186","1141":"1141","1150":"1150","1160":"1160","1180":"1180","1214":"1214","1223":"1223","1200":"1200","1167":"1167","antes 1200":"before 1200","1208":"1208","Viseu, Portugal":"Viseu, Portugal","Lisboa, Lisboa, Portugal":"Lisbon, Lisbon, Portugal","Portugal":"Portugal","nameMeanings":[{"name":"Martins","type":"LAST","attribution":"Dictionary of American Family Names © Patrick Hanks 2003, 2006.","meanings":["Some characteristic forenames:  Spanish Manuel, Jose, Carlos, Fernando, Francisco, Mario, Luis, Armando, Alvaro, Ana, Marcelo, Sergio.  Portuguese Joaquim, Joao, Paulo, Agostinho, Henrique, Afonso, Batista, Ademir, Amadeu, Anabela, Caetano, Heitor.","Portuguese: patronymic from the personal name <i>Martim</i>, from Latin <i>Martinus</i> (see   Martin  ).","Dutch and German: patronymic from the personal name   Martin  . In North America, this surname is also an altered form of the more common Dutch and North German variant   Martens  ."],"variants":[{"name":"Martin","meanings":["English, Scottish, Irish, French, Walloon, Breton, Dutch, Flemish, German, Czech, Slovak, Croatian, Italian (Veneto); Spanish (<b>Martín</b>): from a personal name derived from Latin <i>Martinus</i>, itself a derivative of <i>Mars</i>, genitive <i>Martis</i>, the Roman god of fertility and war, whose name may derive ultimately from a root <i>mar</i> ‘gleam’. This was borne by a famous 4th-century Christian saint, Martin of Tours, and consequently became extremely popular throughout Europe in the Middle Ages. In North America, the surname <i>Martin</i> has absorbed cognates and derivatives from other languages, e.g. Slovak and Rusyn (from Slovakia)   Marcin  , Albanian   Martini  , Polish surnames beginning with <i>Marcin-</i>, and Slovenian patronymics like <b>Martinčič</b> (see   Martincic  ). <i>Martin</i> is the most frequent surname in France and one of the most frequent surnames in Wallonia.","English: variant of   Marton  .","Irish: Anglicized form of Gaelic <b>Ó Mártain</b>, ‘descendant of Martin’ (compare 1 above). Otherwise, a shortened form of   Gilmartin   or   McMartin  ; sometimes also spelled <i>Martyn</i>."]},{"name":"Martinz","meanings":["Portuguese: variant of   Martins  .","Germanized form of Slovenian <b>Martinc</b> or of its variant   Martinec  ."]}]},{"name":"de","type":"LAST","attribution":"Dictionary of American Family Names © Patrick Hanks 2003, 2006.","meanings":["Some characteristic forenames:  Indian Dilip, Anirban, Gopal, Alok, Anindya, Arunava, Asit, Asok, Dibyendu, Goutam, Indra, Indranil.","Indian: variant of   Dey  ."],"variants":[{"name":"Dey","meanings":["Some characteristic forenames:  Indian Ashit, Indu, Naina, Partha, Soumya, Ajit, Anjan, Anjana, Anup, Arjun, Arun, Ashim.","English, Scottish, and Welsh: variant of   Day  .","German: topographic name from a field name in North Rhine-Westphalia, denoting a sizeable piece of land, from Middle Low German <i>dē</i> ‘thigh’ (referring to the shape of the property)."]}]},{"name":"Riba","type":"LAST","attribution":"Dictionary of American Family Names © Patrick Hanks 2003, 2006.","meanings":["Some characteristic forenames:  Jewish Mendel, Yetta.  German Lothar, Erwin, Nikolaus.  Spanish Jose, Alfredo, Carlos, Claudio, Fidel, Manuel, Ramon.","Catalan: topographic name for someone who lived on the bank of a river or the shore of a lake, <i>riba</i> (from Latin <i>ripa</i>), or a habitational name from La Riba, a town in Alt Camp, Tarragona, or any other place called with this word.","Jewish (eastern Ashkenazic): variant of   Ryba  ‘fish’."],"variants":[{"name":"Ryba","meanings":["Polish, Czech, Slovak, Sorbian, and Jewish (eastern Ashkenazic): metonymic occupational name, nickname, or a Jewish artificial name from Polish, Czech, and Slovak <i>ryba</i> ‘fish’. As a metonymic occupational name it may have denoted a fisherman or a seller of fish (see also   Ribar  ,   Rybak  , and   Rybarczyk  ). As a nickname it may have been bestowed on account of some fancied physical resemblance to a fish. The Sorbian surname is found mainly in Germanized forms, such as   Riebe  ."]},{"name":"Riva","meanings":["Some characteristic forenames:  Spanish Carlos, Digna, Mario, Ramon, Sergio, Alvaro, Angel, Armando, Benito, Cristina, Fernando, Guillermo.  Italian Angelo, Flavio, Agostino, Antonio, Italo, Sal, Santo, Sebastiano.  French Gaston, Jean-Paul.","Italian: topographic name for someone who lived by a wharf or landing at a port or seaport or on the bank of a river, from <i>riva</i> ‘river bank’ (from Latin <i>ripa</i>).","Catalan and Spanish: variant of   Riba  , which has the same origin and meaning as 1 above."]},{"name":"Ribas","meanings":["Some characteristic forenames:  Spanish Jose, Manuel, Eduardo, Jorge, Julio, Alberto, Armando, Carlos, Francisco, Mario, Mirta, Rafael.  Portuguese Joao, Paulo.","Catalan: Castilianized form of <b>Ribes</b>, a habitational name from any of the places called with Catalan <i>ribes</i>, plural of <i>riba</i> ‘bank’ (see   Riba  ).","Spanish and Galician: habitational name from any of the places called with the plural of <i>riba</i> ‘bank’ (see   Riba  ). Compare   Rivas  ."]}]},{"name":"de","type":"LAST","attribution":"Dictionary of American Family Names © Patrick Hanks 2003, 2006.","meanings":["Some characteristic forenames:  Indian Dilip, Anirban, Gopal, Alok, Anindya, Arunava, Asit, Asok, Dibyendu, Goutam, Indra, Indranil.","Indian: variant of   Dey  ."],"variants":[{"name":"Dey","meanings":["Some characteristic forenames:  Indian Ashit, Indu, Naina, Partha, Soumya, Ajit, Anjan, Anjana, Anup, Arjun, Arun, Ashim.","English, Scottish, and Welsh: variant of   Day  .","German: topographic name from a field name in North Rhine-Westphalia, denoting a sizeable piece of land, from Middle Low German <i>dē</i> ‘thigh’ (referring to the shape of the property)."]}]},{"name":"Vizela","type":"LAST","attribution":"Dictionary of American Family Names © Patrick Hanks 2003, 2006.","meanings":["Galician and Portuguese: habitational name from any of numerous places called Vilela, from a diminutive of <i>vila</i> ‘village, small town’ (see   Vila  ). Compare   Villela  ."],"variants":[{"name":"Vila","meanings":["Some characteristic forenames:  Spanish Jose, Carlos, Luis, Juan, Manuel, Jorge, Francisco, Pedro, Ramon, Eduardo, Efrain, Enrique.","Catalan: topographic name for someone who lived in a <i>vila</i> (see 3 below), which in Catalonia denoted a small town or village with certain privileges not common for villages, or a habitational name from any of the places called La Vila or Vila. This is one of the most common surnames in Catalonia.","Catalan (<b>Vilà</b>): variant of   Vilar  ."]},{"name":"Villela","meanings":["Some characteristic forenames:  Spanish Jesus, Jose, Pedro, Francisco, Felipe, Javier, Juan, Raymundo, Alfonso, Eduardo, Geraldo, Jose Cruz.","Spanish and Portuguese: altered form of Galician and Portuguese   Vilela  ."]}]},{"name":"Elvira","type":"FIRST","attribution":"Dictionary of First Names © Patrick Hanks and Flavia Hodges 1990, 2003, 2006.","meanings":["name of Germanic (Visigothic) origin , very common in the Middle Ages. It was not used in the English-speaking world until the 19th century, when it was made familiar as the name of the long-suffering wife of  Don Juan , both in  Mozart's  opera Don Giovanni (  1789 ) and in  Byron's  satirical epic poem Don Juan (  1819–24 ). In his comedy Blithe Spirit  Noel Coward  used it as the name of  Charles Condomine's  first wife, who returns to haunt him. It is also the name of the heroine of the Swedish film Elvira Madigan (  1967 ), directed by  Bo Widerberg , a romantic tragedy about a pair of lovers who would rather die than be separated."],"variants":[]}],"lifeSummary":"When Elvira Martins de Riba de Vizela was born in 1153, in Portugal, her father, D. Martim Fernandes - de Riba de Vizela, was -6 and her mother, D. Thereza Estevainha Soares da Silva, was -13. She had at least 3 sons with D. Pedro Mendes de Gandarei Senhor da Quinta de Gondarei. She died in 1223, at the age of 70."},"et":{"1153–1223":"1153–1223","1167–Female":"1167–Surnud","1180–Female":"1180–Surnud","1186–Female":"1186–Surnud","1187–Female":"1187–Surnud","1190–Male":"1190–Surnud","1150–1200":"1150–1200","1141–Male":"1141–Surnud","1143–Male":"1143–Surnud","1200–Male":"1200–Surnud","1160–1208":"1160–1208","1167–1214":"1167–1214","1190":"1190","1143":"1143","1187":"1187","1153":"1153","1186":"1186","1141":"1141","1150":"1150","1160":"1160","1180":"1180","1214":"1214","1223":"1223","1200":"1200","1167":"1167","antes 1200":"enne 1200","1208":"1208","Viseu, Portugal":"Viseu, Portugal","Lisboa, Lisboa, Portugal":"Lisboa, Lisboa, Portugal","Portugal":"Portugal"},"fi":{"1153–1223":"1153–1223","1167–Female":"1167–Kuollut","1180–Female":"1180–Kuollut","1186–Female":"1186–Kuollut","1187–Female":"1187–Kuollut","1190–Male":"1190–Kuollut","1150–1200":"1150–1200","1141–Male":"1141–Kuollut","1143–Male":"1143–Kuollut","1200–Male":"1200–Kuollut","1160–1208":"1160–1208","1167–1214":"1167–1214","1190":"1190","1143":"1143","1187":"1187","1153":"1153","1186":"1186","1141":"1141","1150":"1150","1160":"1160","1180":"1180","1214":"1214","1223":"1223","1200":"1200","1167":"1167","antes 1200":"ennen vuotta 1200","1208":"1208","Viseu, Portugal":"Viseu, Portugali","Lisboa, Lisboa, Portugal":"Lisboa, Lisboa, Portugali","Port